  "slug": "genoa-cake-light-fruit",
  "title": "Genoa cake",
  "subtitle": "The British light fruit cake with glace cherries and citrus peel",
  "excerpt": "A firm, close-textured fruit cake studded with sultanas, glace cherries, and citrus peel. Lighter and less rich than a Christmas cake, Genoa cake is the kind of thing kept in a tin and sliced through the week.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Genoa cake, despite its name, is a British rather than Italian product. It is documented in Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136, as a light fruit cake and appears throughout early twentieth-century British domestic baking literature. The glace cherry and citrus peel combination is the defining characteristic distinguishing it from a plainer sultana loaf.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "About Genoa cake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Genoa cake is a British fruit cake: close-crumbed, firm to slice, and generously fruited. It is lighter than a Christmas cake and keeps for two weeks in a tin without any maturing alcohol needed. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "glacé cherries",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa9u16l00002gv4rgre78xx"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " are the visual signature; the citrus zest and almond extract give the flavour its character.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The cherries should be washed in warm water, dried thoroughly, and tossed in a spoonful of the recipe flour before being folded in. This removes the sticky syrup coating and gives the flour a surface to grip; both steps help prevent the cherries sinking to the base of the cake during baking.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
